Swap, the virtual memory backup.

Swap is disk space that the kernel uses as overflow when ram fills up. Pages of memory that have not been touched in a while can be written out to swap, freeing ram for the processes that need it right now, and when one of those pages is needed again, the kernel reads it back in. It is a safety valve, trading slow disk for the appearance of more memory.

Swap can take one of two forms. A dedicated swap partition is a whole partition set aside for the purpose, common on older installations. A swap file is just an ordinary file used as swap, which is more flexible because you can resize it without re-partitioning, and it is the default on many modern distributions. To set up a swap file you create a file of the size you want, lock its permissions down so only root can read it, which is mandatory, format it as swap with the make-swap command, and then enable it with swap-on. To check what is active, swap-on dash dash show, or the free command, lists your swap; to turn it off you use swap-off, for one area or for all of them. And to make it persistent, you add a line for it in the filesystem table.

There is one important tuning knob, called swappiness. It controls how eagerly the kernel reaches for swap, on a scale where the default is sixty. A lower value tells the kernel to favour keeping things in ram and use swap only reluctantly; a higher value makes it swap more readily. For a desktop the default of sixty is balanced, while on a server a lower value, around ten to twenty, is usually preferred so that active data stays in fast memory. You can change it temporarily with the s-y-s-c-t-l command, and make it permanent in the system control configuration file.
